ğŸ”¹ Euler Path & Euler Circuit

An Euler path is a path that:

Traverses every edge exactly once

Vertices may repeat

An Euler circuit (Euler cycle):

Is an Euler path

Starts and ends at the same vertex

ğŸ“Œ Edges matter, not vertices (BIG GATE TRAP)

ğŸ”¹ Conditions for Euler Graph (UNDIRECTED)

Let G be a connected undirected graph.

âœ… Euler Circuit exists iff:

All vertices have even degree

âœ… Euler Path (but not circuit) exists iff:

Exactly two vertices have odd degree

âŒ No Euler Path:

More than 2 odd-degree vertices

ğŸ“Œ PYQ FAVORITE:
Count odd-degree vertices first.

ğŸ”¹ Euler Path in Directed Graph

For a directed graph:

âœ… Euler Circuit:

In-degree(v) = Out-degree(v) for every vertex

âœ… Euler Path (not circuit):

One vertex: out-degree = in-degree + 1 (start)

One vertex: in-degree = out-degree + 1 (end)

All others: in-degree = out-degree

ğŸ”¹ Hamiltonian Path & Circuit

A Hamiltonian path:

Visits every vertex exactly once

A Hamiltonian circuit:

Hamiltonian path that is closed

ğŸ“Œ Vertices matter, not edges (OPPOSITE of Euler)

ğŸ”¹ Key Differences (VERY IMPORTANT)
Euler	Hamilton
Covers all edges	Covers all vertices
Vertices may repeat	No vertex repetition
Easy necessary & sufficient conditions	No general test
Degree-based	Structural

ğŸ“Œ GATE Trap:
Students mix up conditions.

ğŸ”¹ Important Theorems (For Hamiltonian)

These are sufficient, not necessary.

